# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: media-recorder
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:media-recorder/dataavailable-event] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:media-recorder/dataavailable-event] It’s been available across browsers since April 2021.
[src:media-recorder/dataavailable-event] The **`dataavailable`** event of the `MediaRecorder` interface is fired when the MediaRecorder delivers media data to your application for its use.
[src:media-recorder/dataavailable-event] The data is provided in a `Blob` object that contains the data.
[src:media-recorder/dataavailable-event] Therefore, don't rely on `timeslice` and the number of chunks received to calculate the time elapsed, because errors may accumulate.
[src:media-recorder/dataavailable-event] Instead, keep a separate timer using `Event.timeStamp` or similar, that records the total time elapsed since starting.
[src:media-recorder/dataavailable-event] The `Blob` containing the media data is available in the `dataavailable` event's `data` property.
[src:media-recorder/dataavailable-event] Use the event name in methods like `addEventListener()`, or set an event handler property.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] In **digital recording**, an audio or video signal is converted into a stream of discrete numbers representing the changes over time in air pressure for audio, or chroma and luminance values for video.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] This number stream is saved to a storage device.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] To play back a digital recording, the numbers are retrieved and converted back into their original analog audio or video forms so that they can be heard or seen.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] Because the signal is stored digitally, assuming proper error detection and correction, the recording is not degraded by copying, storage or interference.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] The ADC converts this signal by repeatedly measuring the momentary level of the analog (audio) wave and then assigning a binary number with a given quantity of bits (word length) to each measurement point.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] The longer the word length, the more precise the representation of the original audio wave level.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] The frequency at which the ADC measures the level of the analog wave is called the sample rate or sampling rate.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] The higher the sampling rate, the higher the upper audio frequency of the digitized audio signal.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] The ADC outputs a sequence of digital audio samples that make up a continuous stream of 0s and 1s.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] These binary numbers are stored on recording media such as magnetic tape, a hard drive, optical drive or in solid state memory.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] The DAC converts the numbers back to an analog signal by sticking together the level information stored in each digital sample, thus rebuilding the original analog waveform.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] This signal is amplified and transmitted to the loudspeakers.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] For digital cassettes, the tape head moves as well as the tape, typically in a helical scan configuration, in order to maintain a high enough speed to keep the bits at a manageable size.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] For optical disc recording technologies such as CD-R, a laser is used to alter the optical properties of the dye layer of the medium.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] A weaker laser is used to read these patterns.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] The number of bits used to represent an audio signal directly affects the resulting noise or distortion in a recording.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] As stated by the Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem, to prevent aliasing, the audio signal must be sampled at a rate at least twice that of the highest frequency component in the signal.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] For music-quality audio, 44.1 and 48 kHz sampling rates are the most common.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] Master recording may be done at a higher sampling rate (i.e., 88.2, 96, 176.4 or 192 kHz).
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] High-resolution PCM recordings have been released on DVD-Audio (also known as DVD-A), DualDisc (utilizing the DVD-Audio layer), or High Fidelity Pure Audio on Blu-ray.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] In addition, it is possible to release a high-resolution recording as either an uncompressed WAV or lossless compressed FLAC file (usually at 24 bits) without down-converting it.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] There remains controversy about whether higher sampling rates provide any verifiable benefit to the consumer product.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] When a Compact Disc (the CD Red Book standard is 44.1 kHz 16 bit) is to be made from a high-res recording, the recording must be down-converted to 44.1 kHz.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] This is done as part of the mastering process.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] Beginning in the 1980s, music that was recorded, mixed or mastered digitally was often labeled using the SPARS code to describe which processes were analog and which were digital.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] Since digital recording has become near-ubiquitous, the SPARS codes are now rarely used.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] One of the advantages of digital recording over analog recording is its resistance to errors.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] Once the signal is in the digital format, it is not subject to generation loss from copying.
[src:media-recorder/digital-recording] Instead of the gradual degradation experienced with analog media, digital media is subject to a cliff effect.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder-start] The **`start()`** method of the `MediaRecorder` interface begins recording media into one or more `Blob` objects.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder-start] You can record the entire duration of the media into a single `Blob` (or until you call `requestData()`), or you can specify the number of milliseconds to record at a time.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder-start] Then, each time that amount of media has been recorded, an event will be delivered to let you act upon the recorded media, while a new `Blob` is created to record the next slice of the media.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder-start] Assuming the `MediaRecorder`'s `state` is `inactive`, `start()` sets the `state` to `recording`, then begins capturing media from the input stream.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder-start] A `Blob` is created and the data is collected in it until the time slice period elapses or the source media ends.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder-start] Each time a `Blob` is filled up to that point (the timeslice duration or the end-of-media, if no slice duration was provided), a `dataavailable` event is sent to the `MediaRecorder` with the recorded data.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder-start] If the source is still playing, a new `Blob` is created and recording continues into that, and so forth.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder-start] When the source stream ends, `state` is set to `inactive` and data gathering stops.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder-start] A final `dataavailable` event is sent to the `MediaRecorder`, followed by a `stop` event.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder-start] The number of milliseconds to record into each `Blob`.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder-start] If this parameter isn't included, the entire media duration is recorded into a single `Blob` unless the `requestData()` method is called to obtain the `Blob` and trigger the creation of a new `Blob` into which the media continues to be recorded.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder-start] Errors that can be detected immediately are thrown as DOM exceptions.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder-start] All other errors are reported through `error` events sent to the `MediaRecorder` object.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder-start] You can implement the `onerror` event handler to respond to these errors.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder-start] Thrown if the `MediaRecorder` is not in the `inactive` state; you cannot start recording media if it is already being recorded.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder-start] Thrown if the `MediaStream` is configured to disallow recording.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder-start] This may be the case, for example, with sources obtained using `getUserMedia()` when the user denies permission to use an input device.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder-start] This exception may also be delivered as an `error` event if the security options for the source media change after recording begins.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] The **`MediaRecorder`** interface of the MediaStream Recording API provides functionality to easily record media.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] It is created using the `MediaRecorder()` constructor.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] Creates a new `MediaRecorder` object, given a `MediaStream` to record.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] Options are available to do things like set the container's MIME type (such as `"video/webm"` or `"video/mp4"`) and the bit rates of the audio and video tracks or a single overall bit rate.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] Returns the MIME type that was selected as the recording container for the `MediaRecorder` object when it was created.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] Returns the stream that was passed into the constructor when the `MediaRecorder` was created.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] Returns the video encoding bit rate in use.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] This may differ from the bit rate specified in the constructor (if it was provided).
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] Returns the audio encoding bit rate in use.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] Returns the bitrate mode used to encode audio tracks.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] A static method which returns a `true` or `false` value indicating if the given MIME media type is supported by the current user agent.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] Requests a `Blob` containing the saved data received thus far (or since the last time `requestData()` was called.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] After calling this method, recording continues, but in a new `Blob`.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] Resumes recording of media after having been paused.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] Begins recording media; this method can optionally be passed a `timeslice` argument with a value in milliseconds.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] If this is specified, the media will be captured in separate chunks of that duration, rather than the default behavior of recording the media in a single large chunk.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] Stops recording, at which point a `dataavailable` event containing the final `Blob` of saved data is fired.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] Listen to these events using `addEventListener()` or by assigning an event listener to the `oneventname` property of this interface.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] Fires periodically each time `timeslice` milliseconds of media have been recorded (or when the entire media has been recorded, if `timeslice` wasn't specified).
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] The event, of type `BlobEvent`, contains the recorded media in its `data` property.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] Fired when there are fatal errors that stop recording.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] The received event is based on the `MediaRecorderErrorEvent` interface, whose `error` property contains a `DOMException` that describes the actual error that occurred.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] Fired when media recording resumes after being paused.
[src:media-recorder/mediarecorder] Fired when media recording ends, either when the `MediaStream` ends, or after the `MediaRecorder.stop()` method is called.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] The **MediaStream Recording API**, sometimes referred to as the *Media Recording API* or the *MediaRecorder API*, is closely affiliated with the Media Capture and Streams API and the WebRTC API.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] The MediaStream Recording API makes it possible to capture the data generated by a `MediaStream` or `HTMLMediaElement` object for analysis, processing, or saving to disk.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] It's also surprisingly easy to work with.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] The MediaStream Recording API is comprised of a single major interface, `MediaRecorder`, which does all the work of taking the data from a `MediaStream` and delivering it to you for processing.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] The data is delivered by a series of `dataavailable` events, already in the format you specify when creating the `MediaRecorder`.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] You can then process the data further or write it to file as desired.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] Create a `MediaRecorder` object, specifying the source stream and any desired options (such as the container's MIME type or the desired bit rates of its tracks).
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] Set `ondataavailable` to an event handler for the `dataavailable` event; this will be called whenever data is available for you.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] Once the source media is playing and you've reached the point where you're ready to record video, call `MediaRecorder.start()` to begin recording.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] Your `dataavailable` event handler gets called every time there's data ready for you to do with as you will; the event has a `data` attribute whose value is a `Blob` that contains the media data.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] You can force a `dataavailable` event to occur, thereby delivering the latest sound to you so you can filter it, save it, or whatever.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] Recording stops automatically when the source media stops playing.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] You can stop recording at any time by calling `MediaRecorder.stop()`.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] If anything goes wrong during recording, an `error` event is sent to the `MediaRecorder`.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] You can listen for `error` events by setting up a `onerror` event handler.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] Example here, we use an HTML Canvas as source of the `MediaStream`, and stop recording after 9 seconds.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] You can also use the properties of the `MediaRecorder` object to determine the state of the recording process, and its `pause()` and `resume()` methods to pause and resume recording of the source media.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] If you need or want to check to see if a specific MIME type is supported, that's possible as well.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] Just call `MediaRecorder.isTypeSupported()`.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] If your goal is to record camera and/or microphone input, you may wish to examine the available input devices before beginning the process of constructing the `MediaRecorder`.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] To do so, you'll need to call `navigator.mediaDevices.enumerateDevices()` to get a list of the available media devices.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] You can then examine that list and identify the potential input sources, and even filter the list based on desired criteria.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] In this code snippet, `enumerateDevices()` is used to examine the available input devices, locate those which are audio input devices, and create `<option>` elements that are then added to a `<select>` element representing an input source picker.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] Code similar to this can be used to let the user restrict the set of devices they wish to use.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] To learn more about using the MediaStream Recording API, see Using the MediaStream Recording API, which shows how to use the API to record audio clips.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] A second article, Recording a media element, describes how to receive a stream from an `<audio>` or `<video>` element and use the captured stream (in this case, recording it and saving it to a local disk).
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] Each time a chunk of media data is finished being recorded, it's delivered to consumers in `Blob` form using a `BlobEvent` of type `dataavailable`.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] The primary interface that implements the MediaStream Recording API.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] The interface that represents errors thrown by the MediaStream Recording API.
[src:media-recorder/mediastream-recording-api] Its `error` property is a `DOMException` that specifies that error occurred.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] A **screencast** is a digital recording of computer screen output, also known as a **video screen capture** or a **screen recording**, often containing audio narration.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] The term *screencast* compares with the related term *screenshot*; whereas screenshot generates a single picture of a computer screen, a screencast is essentially a movie of the changes over time that a user sees on a computer screen, that can be enhanced with audio narration and captions.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] In 2004, columnist Jon Udell invited readers of his blog to propose names for the emerging genre.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] Udell selected the term "screencast", which was proposed by both Joseph McDonald and Deeje Cooley.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] The terms "screencast," "screencam" and "screen recording" are often used interchangeably, due to the market influence of ScreenCam as a screencasting product of the early 1990s.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] ScreenCam, however, is a federal trademark in the United States, whereas screencast is not trademarked and has established use in publications as part of Internet and computing vernacular.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] Screen recording is now the most generic term.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] Screencasts can help demonstrate and teach the use of software features.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] Creating a screencast helps software developers show off their work.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] Educators may also use screencasts as another means of integrating technology into the curriculum.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] Students can record video and audio as they demonstrate the proper procedure to solve a problem on an interactive whiteboard.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] Screencasts are useful tools for ordinary software users as well: They help filing report bugs in which the screencasts take the place of potentially unclear written explanations; they help showing others how a given task is accomplished in a specific software environment.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] Organizers of seminars may choose to routinely record complete seminars and make them available to all attendees for future reference and/or sell these recordings to people who cannot afford the fee of the live seminar or do not have the time to attend it.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] This will generate an additional revenue stream for the organizers and makes the knowledge available to a broader audience.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] This strategy of recording seminars is already widely used in fields where using a simple video camera or audio recorder is insufficient to make a useful recording of a seminar.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] Computer-related seminars need high quality and easily readable recordings of screen contents which is usually not achieved by a video camera that records the desktop.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] In classrooms, teachers and students can use this tool to create videos to explain content, vocabulary, etc.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] Videos can make class time more productive for both teachers and students.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] Screencasts may increase student engagement and achievement and also provide more time in which students can work collaboratively in groups, so screencasts help them to think through cooperative learning.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] In addition, screencasts allow students to move at their own pace since they can pause or review content anytime and anywhere.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] Screencasts are excellent for those learners who just need an oral as well as a visual explanation of the content presented.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] Open-source tools exist for both screencasting and livestreaming the recorded video.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] Trial versions of screencasting programs often apply a watermark, encouraging users to purchase the full version in order to remove it.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] An alternative solution for capturing a screencast is the use of a hardware RGB or DVI frame grabber card.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] This approach places the burden of the recording and compression process on a machine separate from the one generating the visual material being captured.
[src:media-recorder/screencast] The films *Unfriended*, *Unfriended: Dark Web*, and *Searching* contain screencasts that were simulated for the purposes of the film.
